        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Understanding the Options</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">In Australia, there are four main ways to finance a vehicle: a car loan (secured or unsecured), a novated lease (for salaried employees), a finance lease (for business), and a chattel mortgage (for business). Each has different implications for ownership, tax, cash flow, and flexibility. The operating lease is a fifth option, used primarily for fleet management. Understanding the differences is essential for making the right choice.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A car loan is the simplest and most common option for personal vehicle purchases in Australia. You borrow money, buy the car, own it from day one, and repay the loan over 1-7 years. Once the loan is paid off, the car is yours free and clear. There are no residual payments, no balloon requirements, and no restrictions on vehicle use or modifications. You can sell the car at any time (with lender consent if secured). For the majority of Australian personal car buyers, a standard secured car loan is the right choice.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A novated lease is a salary sacrifice arrangement available only to salaried employees. Your employer deducts lease payments and running costs from your pre-tax salary, reducing your taxable income. For eligible battery electric vehicles, the FBT exemption makes this the most tax-effective vehicle finance option available in Australia. For petrol and diesel vehicles, the tax savings are smaller but still meaningful for employees in higher tax brackets (32.5%+).</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A finance lease is a business finance product. The finance company buys the vehicle and leases it to your business. You make regular lease payments plus a residual (balloon) at the end. The vehicle does not appear on your balance sheet (off-balance-sheet finance). GST is claimed progressively on lease payments. At the end of the lease, you either pay the residual to own the car, refinance, or return it.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A chattel mortgage is also for business use. You own the vehicle from day one, and the lender holds a mortgage over it. You claim GST on purchase upfront (in your next BAS), deduct interest, and depreciate the vehicle. Most popular structure for ABN holders, sole traders, and businesses that want immediate ownership and maximum upfront tax benefits.</p>
        </section>
