  <section class="py-16 bg-gray-50"><div class="max-w-[100rem] mx-auto px-8"><div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-8 text-center">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">Is a car lease cheaper than a car loan?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">It depends on your tax bracket, employment status, and vehicle type. For salaried employees in the 32.5%+ tax bracket leasing an FBT-exempt EV, a novated lease is significantly cheaper. For personal buyers not eligible for salary packaging, a car loan is usually the better option.</p></div></details>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden mt-3"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">Do I own the car at the end of a lease?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">Not automatically. At the end of a novated or finance lease, you must pay the residual value to take ownership. With a car loan, you own the car from day one and there is nothing to pay at the end (unless you chose a balloon payment).</p></div></details>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden mt-3"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">What is the residual value?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">The residual is a lump sum due at the end of a lease or a loan with a balloon payment. For leases, the ATO sets minimum residual percentages based on the lease term. You can pay it in cash, refinance it, or trade the vehicle in. A higher residual reduces regular payments but means a larger sum at the end.</p></div></details>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden mt-3"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">Can I salary sacrifice a car loan instead of a novated lease?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">Not effectively. While some employers allow salary sacrifice of car loan repayments, the FBT implications make this less tax-effective than a properly structured novated lease. Salary sacrificing a car loan does not provide the same GST savings or bundled running cost benefits.</p></div></details>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden mt-3"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">What about operating leases?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">An operating lease is a fully maintained rental arrangement used primarily by businesses for fleet vehicles. The leasing company owns the vehicle, handles all maintenance and running costs, and you return the vehicle at the end. There is no ownership transfer. Operating leases are uncommon for individual buyers.</p></div></details>
        <details class="group border border-gray-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden mt-3"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-6 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors"><h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-[#1e3a5f] pr-8 text-left">Which is best for an electric vehicle?</h3><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-[#10b981] flex-shrink-0 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="p-6 pt-0 border-t border-gray-100"><p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">For salaried employees, a novated lease with the FBT exemption is the clear winner for EVs. For self-employed or business use, a chattel mortgage offers GST recovery and depreciation. For personal use without salary packaging, a green car loan offers discounted rates from 5.09% p.a.</p></div></details>
